#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:11
#, no-c-format
msgid "&sudo; basics"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:18
#, no-c-format
msgid "Running certain commands requires root privileges. However, for security reasons and to avoid mistakes, it is not recommended to log in as &rootuser;. A safer approach is to log in as a regular user, and then use &sudo; to run commands with elevated privileges."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:24
#, no-c-format
msgid "On &productname;, &sudo; is configured to work similarly to <command>su</command> . However, &sudo; provides a flexible mechanism that allows users to run commands with privileges of any other user. This can be used to assign roles with specific privileges to certain users and groups. For example, it is possible to allow members of the group &examplegroup; to run a command with the privileges of user &exampleuserII;. Access to the command can be further restricted by disallowing any command options. While su always requires the &rootuser; password for authentication with PAM, &sudo; can be configured to authenticate with your own credentials. This means that the users do not need to share the &rootuser; password, which improves security."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:38
#, no-c-format
msgid "Basic &sudo; usage"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:40
#, no-c-format
msgid "The following chapter provides an introduction to basic usage of &sudo;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:45
#, no-c-format
msgid "Running a single command"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:46
#, no-c-format
msgid "As a regular user, you can run any command as &rootuser; by adding &sudo; before it. This prompts you to provide the root password. If authenticated successfully, this runs the command as &rootuser;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:51
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "&prompt.user;<command>id -un</command><co xml:id=\"co-sudo-usage-id\"/>\n"
      "tux\n"
      "&prompt.sudo;<command>id -un</command>\n"
      "root's password:<co xml:id=\"co-sudo-usage-pw\"/>\n"
      "root\n"
      "&prompt.user;<command>id -un</command>\n"
      "tux<co xml:id=\"co-sudo-usage-after\"/>\n"
      "&prompt.sudo;<command>id -un</command>\n"
      "<co xml:id=\"co-sudo-usage-nopw\"/>\n"
      "root\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:65
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <command>id -un</command> command prints the login name of the current user."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:71
#, no-c-format
msgid "The password is not shown during input, neither as clear text nor as masking characters."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:77
#, no-c-format
msgid "Only commands that start with &sudo; run with elevated privileges."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:82
#, no-c-format
msgid "The elevated privileges persist for a certain period of time, so you do not need to provide the &rootuser; password again."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:89
#, no-c-format
msgid "I/O redirection"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:90
#, no-c-format
msgid "When using &sudo;, I/O redirection does not work:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:93
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "&prompt.sudo;echo s &gt; /proc/sysrq-trigger\n"
      "bash: /proc/sysrq-trigger: Permission denied\n"
      "&prompt.sudo;cat &lt; /proc/1/maps\n"
      "bash: /proc/1/maps: Permission denied\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:99
#, no-c-format
msgid "In the example above, only the <command>echo</command> and <command>cat</command> commands run with elevated privileges. The redirection is done by the user's shell with user privileges. To perform redirection with elevated privileges, either start a shell as in <xref linkend=\"sec-sudo-shell\"/> or use the <command>dd</command> utility:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:108
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "echo s | sudo dd of=/proc/sysrq-trigger\n"
      "sudo dd if=/proc/1/maps | cat <!-- TODO: Better example! -->\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:116
#, no-c-format
msgid "Starting a shell"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:117
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using &sudo; every time to run a command with elevated privileges is not always practical. While you can use the <command>sudo bash</command> command, it is recommended to use one of the built-in mechanisms to start a shell:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:125
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>sudo -s (&lt;command&gt;)</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:127
#, no-c-format
msgid "Starts a shell specified by the <envar>SHELL</envar> environment variable or the target user's default shell. If a command is specified, it is passed to the shell (with the <option>-c</option> option). Otherwise the shell runs in interactive mode."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:134
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>sudo -s\n"
      "root's password:\n"
      "<prompt>root:/home/tux # </prompt>exit\n"
      "<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:143
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>sudo -i (&lt;command&gt;)</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:145
#, no-c-format
msgid "Similar to <option>-s</option> , but starts the shell as a login shell. This means that the shell's start-up files ( <filename>.profile</filename> etc.) are processed, and the current working directory is set to the target user's home directory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:152
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>sudo -i\n"
      "root's password:\n"
      "<prompt>root:~ # </prompt>exit\n"
      "<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:162
#, no-c-format
msgid "Environment variables"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:163
#, no-c-format
msgid "By default, &sudo; does not propagate environment variables. This behavior can be changed using the <literal>env_reset</literal> option (see <xref linkend=\"tab-adm-sudo-options\"/> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:173
#, no-c-format
msgid "Configuring &sudo;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:175
#, no-c-format
msgid "&sudo; provides a wide range on configurable options."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:180
#, no-c-format
msgid "Locked yourself out of sudo"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:181
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you accidentally locked yourself out of &sudo;, use <command>su -</command> and the &rootuser; password to start a root shell. To fix the error, run <command>visudo</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:231
#, no-c-format
msgid "Example configurations are for demonstration purposes only"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:232
#, no-c-format
msgid "The example rules outlined below are purely for demonstration purposes. Use them to understand the general syntax of &sudo; configuration files. Do not use them in real-world setups, because they do not reflect the complexity of these environments."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:240
#, no-c-format
msgid "&sudo; configuration best practices"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:241
#, no-c-format
msgid "Before your start, a few ground rules for maintaining &sudo; configurations follow:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:246
#, no-c-format
msgid "Always use <command>visudo</command> to edit &sudo; configuration files"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:248
#, no-c-format
msgid "Any changes to the &sudo; configuration should be done using the <command>visudo</command> command. <command>visudo</command> is a tailor-made tool that allows you to edit the &sudo; configuration files and runs basic syntax checks, making sure that the configuration remains intact and functional. A faulty &sudo; configuration can result in a user being locked out of their own system."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:259
#, no-c-format
msgid "Always create custom configurations under <filename>/etc/sudoers.d/</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:261
#, no-c-format
msgid "Custom configurations must reside under <filename>/etc/sudoers.d/</filename> to be pulled in by &sudo;. Settings in the custom configuration files take precedence over the ones in the default configuration in <filename>/etc/sudoers</filename> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:270
#, no-c-format
msgid "Always mind the order in which configurations are read"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:272
#, no-c-format
msgid "To make sure the custom configurations are read in the correct order, prefix them with numbers. Use leading zeroes to establish the order in which the files are read. For example, <filename>01_myfirstconfig</filename> is parsed before <filename>10_myotherconfig</filename> . If a directive has been set in a file that is read before another file that contains conflicting information, the last-read directive is applied."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:283
#, no-c-format
msgid "Always use descriptive file names"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:285
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use file names that hint at what the configuration file does. This helps you keep track of what your &sudo; setup is supposed to do."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:296
#, no-c-format
msgid "Create a &sudo; configuration file that allows a normal user (&exampleuser;) to use the <command>useradd</command> command with their own password instead of the &rootuser; password."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:302
#, no-c-format
msgid "Create a user-specific configuration file"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:305
#, no-c-format
msgid "As system administrator (&rootuser;), create a custom configuration file that holds the new user-specific directives by starting <command>visudo</command> . Use both numbering and a descriptive name:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:310
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "  &prompt.root;<command>visudo -f /etc/sudoers.d/02_usermanagement</command>\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:315
#, no-c-format
msgid "Create a rule that allows &exampleuser; to execute the <command>/usr/sbin/useradd</command> binary in the entire environment that this &sudo; configuration is applied to:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:320
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "  &exampleuser_plain;<co xml:id=\"co-who\"/> ALL<co xml:id=\"co-where\"/> = /usr/sbin/useradd<co xml:id=\"co-what\"/>\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:325
#, no-c-format
msgid "Specify the user or group. List users by name or <literal>#UID</literal> , and groups by <literal>%GROUPNAME</literal> . Separate multiple items with commas. To negate entries, use <literal>!</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:332
#, no-c-format
msgid "Specify one or several (separated by commas) hosts. Use (fully qualified) host names or IP addresses. Add <literal>ALL</literal> to enforce this setting globally across all hosts. Use <literal>!</literal> for negations."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:340
#, no-c-format
msgid "Specify one or several executables (separated by commas). When specifying them, make sure to mind the following rules:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:346
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>/usr/sbin/useradd</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:348
#, no-c-format
msgid "Without any additional options added, this allows the execution of every possible <command>useradd</command> command."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:355
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>/usr/sbin/useradd -c</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:357
#, no-c-format
msgid "If you explicitly specify an option, then that option is the only one that is allowed. Nothing else would be available to the user you specified above."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:365
#, no-c-format
msgid "<command>/usr/sbin/useradd \"\"</command>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:367
#, no-c-format
msgid "This would just let the user invoke a mere <command>useradd</command> without any option at all."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:374
#, no-c-format
msgid "In the example above, you would want to either allow all options and subcommands or limit them to a few for security reasons, but forbidding a user to specify any option at all would be pointless in this context."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:384
#, no-c-format
msgid "To let the user use their own password instead of the &rootuser; password, add the following line:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:388
#, no-c-format
msgid "Defaults:&exampleuser_plain; !targetpw\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:390
#, no-c-format
msgid "When active, this flag requires the user to enter the password of the target user, i.e. &rootuser;. This flag is enabled by default on any &productname; system. Negate it using <literal>!</literal> to require the user to just enter their own password instead of the &rootuser; password."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:410
#, no-c-format
msgid "Modify the configuration from <xref linkend=\"ex-sudo-custom-config-user\"/> so that a group of named users can run the <command>useradd</command> command without the need for the &rootuser; password. Also, add the <command>usermod</command> and <command>userdel</command> to the list of commands available to this group."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:418
#, no-c-format
msgid "Create custom configurations by grouping items"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:421
#, no-c-format
msgid "To modify the example configuration, open it as system administrator with <command>visudo</command> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:425
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;<command>visudo /etc/sudoers.d/02_usermanagement</command>\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:429
#, no-c-format
msgid "Add more users to the rule in a comma-separated list:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:432
#, no-c-format
msgid "&exampleuser_plain;, &exampleuserII_plain; ALL = /usr/sbin/useradd\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:436
#, no-c-format
msgid "To allow the listed users to execute a list of commands, specify the commands as a comma-separated list:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:440
#, no-c-format
msgid "&exampleuser_plain;, &exampleuserII_plain; ALL = /usr/sbin/useradd, /usr/sbin/usermod, /usr/sbin/userdel\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:444
#, no-c-format
msgid "To let the listed users use their own password instead of the &rootuser; password, add the following line:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:448
#, no-c-format
msgid "Defaults:&exampleuser_plain;, &exampleuserII_plain; !targetpw\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:450
#, no-c-format
msgid "When active, this flag requires the listed users to enter the password of the target user, i.e. &rootuser;. This flag is enabled by default on any &productname; system. Negate it using <literal>!</literal> to require the listed users to just enter their own password instead of the &rootuser; password."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:470
#, no-c-format
msgid "Use aliases to simplify your custom configuration from <xref linkend=\"ex-sudo-custom-config-group\"/> even further. Grouping items helps to a certain extent, but using global aliases for users, commands and hosts is the most efficient way to keep a clean and lean &sudo; configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:477
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using aliases and groups instead of lists is a much better way to address changes in your setup. Should a user leave, just remove them from the global <literal>User_Alias</literal> declaration in your alias declaration file instead of scouring all the separate custom configuration files. The same procedure applies for any other type of alias ( <literal>Host_Alias</literal> , <literal>Cmnd_Alias</literal> and <literal>Runas_Alias</literal> )."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:487
#, no-c-format
msgid "Simplify configurations by applying aliases"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:490
#, no-c-format
msgid "Create a new file to hold your global alias definitions:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:493
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;<command>visudo /etc/sudoers.d/01_aliases</command>\n"
      "  "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:497
#, no-c-format
msgid "Add the following line to create the <literal>TEAMLEADERS</literal> alias:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:501
#, no-c-format
msgid "User_Alias    TEAMLEADERS = &exampleuser_plain;, &exampleuserII_plain;\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:505
#, no-c-format
msgid "Add the following line to create the <literal>USERMANAGEMENT</literal> alias:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:508
#, no-c-format
msgid "Cmnd_Alias    USERMANAGEMENT = /usr/sbin/useradd, /usr/sbin/usermod, /usr/sbin/userdel\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:512
#, no-c-format
msgid "Save your changes and exit <command>visudo</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:517
#, no-c-format
msgid "As system administrator, start <command>visudo</command> to edit the example configuration file:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:521
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.root;<command>visudo -f /etc/sudoers.d/02_usermanagement</command>\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:525
#, no-c-format
msgid "Delete the previous rule and replace it with the following rule that uses the aliases you have just defined above:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:529
#, no-c-format
msgid "TEAMLEADERS ALL = USERMANAGEMENT\n"
      "            "
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:533
#, no-c-format
msgid "To let all the users defined by <literal>User_Alias</literal> use their own password instead of the &rootuser; password, add the following line:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:538
#, no-c-format
msgid "Defaults:TEAMLEADERS !targetpw"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:541
#, no-c-format
msgid "Save the configuration, leave the editor and open a second shell to test whether &sudo; honors your new configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:551
#, no-c-format
msgid "Basic sudoers configuration syntax"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:552
#, no-c-format
msgid "The sudoers configuration files contain two types of options: strings and flags. While strings can contain any value, flags can be turned either ON or OFF. The most important syntax constructs for sudoers configuration files are as follows:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:558
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "# Everything on a line after # is ignored <co xml:id=\"co-sudo-syntax-comment\"/>\n"
      "Defaults !insults # Disable the insults flag <co xml:id=\"co-sudo-syntax-flag\"/>\n"
      "Defaults env_keep += \"DISPLAY HOME\" # Add DISPLAY and HOME to env_keep\n"
      "&exampleuser_plain; ALL = NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/frobnicate, PASSWD: /usr/bin/journalctl <co xml:id=\"co-sudo-syntax-rule\"/>\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:566
#, no-c-format
msgid "There are two exceptions: <literal>#include</literal> and <literal>#includedir</literal> are regular commands."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:572
#, no-c-format
msgid "Remove the <literal>!</literal> character to set the desired flag to ON."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:578
#, no-c-format
msgid "See <xref linkend=\"sec-sudo-conf-rule\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:584
#, no-c-format
msgid "Useful flags and options"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:586
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>targetpw</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:588
#, no-c-format
msgid "This flag controls whether the invoking user is required to enter the password of the target user (ON) (for example &rootuser;) or the invoking user (OFF)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:593
#, no-c-format
msgid "Defaults targetpw # Turn targetpw flag ON"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:597
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>rootpw</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:599
#, no-c-format
msgid "If set, &sudo; prompts for the &rootuser; password. The default is OFF."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:603
#, no-c-format
msgid "Defaults !rootpw # Turn rootpw flag OFF"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:607
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>env_reset</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:609
#, no-c-format
msgid "If set, &sudo; constructs a minimal environment with <envar>TERM</envar> , <envar>PATH</envar> , <envar>HOME</envar> , <envar>MAIL</envar> , <envar>SHELL</envar> , <envar>LOGNAME</envar> , <envar>USER</envar> , <envar>USERNAME</envar> , and <envar>SUDO_*</envar> . Additionally, variables listed in <literal>env_keep</literal> are imported from the calling environment. The default is ON."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:618
#, no-c-format
msgid "Defaults env_reset # Turn env_reset flag ON"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:622
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>env_keep</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:624
#, no-c-format
msgid "List of environment variables to keep when the <literal>env_reset</literal> flag is ON."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:628
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "# Set env_keep to contain EDITOR and PROMPT\n"
      "Defaults env_keep = \"EDITOR PROMPT\"\n"
      "Defaults env_keep += \"JRE_HOME\" # Add JRE_HOME\n"
      "Defaults env_keep -= \"JRE_HOME\" # Remove JRE_HOME\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:637
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>env_delete</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:639
#, no-c-format
msgid "List of environment variables to remove when the <literal>env_reset</literal> flag is OFF."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:643
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "# Set env_delete to contain EDITOR and PROMPT\n"
      "Defaults env_delete = \"EDITOR PROMPT\"\n"
      "Defaults env_delete += \"JRE_HOME\" # Add JRE_HOME\n"
      "Defaults env_delete -= \"JRE_HOME\" # Remove JRE_HOME\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:652
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <literal>Defaults</literal> token can also be used to create aliases for a collection of users, hosts, and commands. Furthermore, it is possible to apply an option only to a specific set of users."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:657
#, no-c-format
msgid "For detailed information about the sudoers configuration files, consult <command>man 5 sudoers</command> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:664
#, no-c-format
msgid "Basic sudoers rules"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:665
#, no-c-format
msgid "Each rule follows the following scheme ( <literal>[]</literal> marks optional parts):"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:669
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "#Who      Where         As whom      Tag                What\n"
      "User_List Host_List = [(User_List)] [NOPASSWD:|PASSWD:] Cmnd_List\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:674
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudoers rule syntax"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:676
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>User_List</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:678
#, no-c-format
msgid "One or several (separated by comma) identifiers: either a user name, a group in the format <literal>%GROUPNAME</literal> , or a user ID in the format <literal>#UID</literal> . Negation can be specified with the <literal>!</literal> prefix."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:687
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>Host_List</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:689
#, no-c-format
msgid "One or several (separated by comma) identifiers: either a (fully qualified) host name or an IP address. Negation can be specified with the <literal>!</literal> prefix. <literal>ALL</literal> is a common choice for <literal>Host_List</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:698
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>NOPASSWD:|PASSWD:</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:700
#, no-c-format
msgid "The user is not prompted for a password when running commands matching <literal>Cmd_List</literal> after <literal>NOPASSWD:</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:705
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>PASSWD</literal> is the default. It only needs to be specified when both <literal>PASSWD</literal> and <literal>NOPASSWD</literal> are on the same line:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:710
#, no-c-format
msgid "&exampleuser_plain; ALL = PASSWD: /usr/bin/foo, NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/bar"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: adm_sudo.xml:714
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>Cmnd_List</literal>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:716
#, no-c-format
msgid "One or several (separated by comma) specifiers: a path to an executable, followed by an optional allowed argument."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:720
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "/usr/bin/foo     # Anything allowed\n"
      "/usr/bin/foo bar # Only \"/usr/bin/foo bar\" allowed\n"
      "/usr/bin/foo \"\"  # No arguments allowed\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:728
#, no-c-format
msgid "<literal>ALL</literal> can be used as <literal>User_List</literal> , <literal>Host_List</literal> , and <literal>Cmnd_List</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:732
#, no-c-format
msgid "A rule that allows &exampleuser; to run all commands as root without entering a password:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:736
#, no-c-format
msgid "&exampleuser_plain; ALL = NOPASSWD: ALL"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:737
#, no-c-format
msgid "A rule that allows &exampleuser; to run <command>systemctl restart apache2</command> :"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:741
#, no-c-format
msgid "&exampleuser_plain; ALL = /usr/bin/systemctl restart apache2"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:742
#, no-c-format
msgid "A rule that allows &exampleuser; to run <command>wall</command> as <systemitem>admin</systemitem> with no arguments:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:746
#, no-c-format
msgid "&exampleuser_plain; ALL = (admin) /usr/bin/wall \"\""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:748
#, no-c-format
msgid "Unsafe rules"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:749
#, no-c-format
msgid "<emphasis>Do not</emphasis> use rules like <literal>ALL ALL = ALL</literal> without <literal>Defaults targetpw</literal> . Otherwise anyone can run commands as &rootuser;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:756
#, no-c-format
msgid "Winbind and sudo"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:757
#, no-c-format
msgid "When specifying the group name in the <filename>sudoers</filename> file, make sure that you use the NetBIOS domain name instead of the realm, for example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:762
#, no-c-format
msgid "<replaceable>%DOMAIN</replaceable>\\\\<replaceable>GROUP_NAME</replaceable> ALL = (ALL) ALL"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:763
#, no-c-format
msgid "Keep in mind that when using winbindd, the format also depends on the <option>winbind separator</option> option in the <filename>smb.conf</filename> file. By default, it is <literal>\\</literal> . If it is changed, for example, to <literal>+</literal> , then the account format in the <filename>sudoers</filename> file must be <literal>DOMAIN+GROUP_NAME</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:777
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using &sudo; with &xvendor; applications"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:778
#, no-c-format
msgid "Starting graphical applications with &sudo; normally results in the following error:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:782
#, no-c-format
msgid "\n"
      "&prompt.sudo;xterm\n"
      "xterm: Xt error: Can't open display: %s\n"
      "xterm: DISPLAY is not set\n"
      ""
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:787
#, no-c-format
msgid "A simple workaround is to use xhost to temporarily allow the root user to access the local user's X session. This is done using the following command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:792
#, no-c-format
msgid "xhost si:localuser:root"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:793
#, no-c-format
msgid "The command below removes the granted access:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:796
#, no-c-format
msgid "xhost -si:localuser:root"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:798
#, no-c-format
msgid "Potential security issue"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:799
#, no-c-format
msgid "Running graphical applications with root privileges has security implications. It is recommended to enable root access for a graphical application only as an exception. It is also recommended to revoke the granted root access as soon as the graphical application is closed."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:809
#, no-c-format
msgid "More information"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:811
#, no-c-format
msgid "The <command>sudo --help</command> command offers a brief overview of the available command line options, while the <command>man sudoers</command> command provides detailed information about <filename>sudoers</filename> and its configuration."
msgstr ""

